text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Front Rounded Vowels: Comparing English and Turkish%0a%0a:Author: aditti%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIllustrating the differences in vowel systems for English and Turkish in terms of the Vowel Quadrangle%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aVowels can be classified according to multiple criteria - height of tongue body (high/mid/low), backness of tongue body (front/central/back), and position of lips (rounded/unrounded). Front rounded vowels are those which require rounding of lips and tongue placement at the front without air constriction.%0a%0aIn English, there are no such vowels which can be observed in the English IPA chart for vowels. However, in Turkish out of the 8 vowels (⟨a⟩, ⟨e⟩, ⟨ı⟩, ⟨i⟩, ⟨o⟩, ⟨ö⟩, ⟨u⟩, ⟨ü⟩), 2 of them are front rounded vowels. These are %3cö> (front rounded mid vowel) with phoneme [œ], used in words like %3cgöz> (meaning “eye”), pronounced as /ˈɟœz/. The other is %3cü> (front rounded high vowel) with phoneme [y], used in words like %3cgüneş> (meaning “sun”), pronounced as /ɟyˈneʃ/.Turkish has a two-dimensional vowel harmony system (backness harmony, rounding harmony) that leverages these vowels. Front vowels (e, i, ö, ü) are followed by front vowels, back vowels (a, ı, o, u) are followed by back vowels. Additionally, rounded vowels (o, ö, u, ü) are followed by closed rounded (u, ü) or open unrounded (a, e) vowels, and unrounded vowels (a, e, ı, i) are followed by unrounded vowels. In English, all front and central vowels are unrounded, and all back vowels are rounded, thereby creating a system where roundness is predictable based on the backness of the tongue. %0a%0a%0aEnglish Vowels IPA: https://phoible.org/inventories/view/2178#tipa %0aTurkish Vowels IPA: https://phoible.org/inventories/view/186#tipa %0aVowel Harmony in Turkish: https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Turkish/Pronunciation_and_Alphabet/Vowel_Classifications_and_Harmony#:~:text=In%2520short%253A%2520Rounded%2520vowels%2520(o,are%2520followed%2520by%2520unrounded%2520vowels. %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: A:)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a(:Title: Front Rounded Vowels: Comparing English and Turkish:)
